WEBVTT

00:00.467 --> 00:03.068
<i>OLDER TED:</i>
<i>In the spring of 2009,</i>
<i>I'd been hired to design</i>

00:03.070 --> 00:05.571
<i>a new headquarters for</i>
<i>Goliath National Bank.</i>

00:05.573 --> 00:08.807
<i>And I was eager</i>
<i>to add as much of my</i>
<i>voice as an architect</i>

00:08.809 --> 00:10.342
<i>into the plans as possible.</i>

00:10.344 --> 00:15.180
Wood beams bathed
in natural light
in the atrium.

00:16.049 --> 00:17.149
They're gonna love it!

00:17.151 --> 00:21.954
<i>There was</i>
<i>only one problem,</i>
<i>and his name was Bilson.</i>

00:21.956 --> 00:24.857
Wood? Natural light?

00:24.859 --> 00:25.724
Uh, no!

00:25.726 --> 00:29.261
Natural light
reminds the workers that
there is an outside world

00:29.263 --> 00:33.799
where they have
family and friends.
We want to crush that!

00:33.801 --> 00:36.769
You show up in the dark,
you go home in the dark.

00:36.771 --> 00:40.806
You spend your whole
damn day in the dark!

00:40.808 --> 00:43.275
(WHISPERING) I need
to hear Lily's voice.

00:43.277 --> 00:45.377
Who said you could leave?

00:45.379 --> 00:49.014
<i>OLDER TED:</i>
<i>Bilson was killing</i>
<i>every original idea I had.</i>

00:49.016 --> 00:51.083
<i>Then, one day, GNB</i>
<i>took him off the</i>
<i>project</i>

00:51.085 --> 00:54.453
<i>and created</i>
<i>a new task force</i>
<i>to oversee my designs.</i>

00:54.455 --> 00:56.021
<i>Suddenly,</i>
<i>everything changed.</i>

00:56.023 --> 00:59.091
We'll have
a rooftop Zen garden
for quiet contemplation.

00:59.093 --> 01:01.360
We'll have
a reflecting pool
in the lobby where

01:01.362 --> 01:04.663
local children can
come to make wishes.

01:04.665 --> 01:07.699
The new GNB,
a place of work

01:08.234 --> 01:10.569
that you can call home.

01:11.237 --> 01:13.705
Thank you, and, um,

01:14.207 --> 01:15.841
welcome home.

01:17.944 --> 01:19.745
(ALL EXCLAIMING)

01:21.147 --> 01:23.215
<i>OLDER TED:</i>
<i>Everything</i>
<i>was going great,</i>

01:23.217 --> 01:25.984
<i>until one day,</i>
<i>in the elevator...</i>

01:26.619 --> 01:28.053
(CLEARS THROAT)

01:29.155 --> 01:30.589
Whoa!

01:32.325 --> 01:33.759
Yeah, it's Ted.

01:33.761 --> 01:36.095
No, no, no, no. I did
not approve that change

01:36.097 --> 01:38.764
for the blueprints
for the new GNB
headquarters

01:38.766 --> 01:42.668
for which I'm
the head architect
at only 30 years old.

01:42.670 --> 01:45.871
(CHUCKLING)
Yes, I'm single
and I give to charity.

01:45.873 --> 01:47.973
What does that have
to do with anything?

01:47.975 --> 01:51.009
All right,
goodbye, Mr. Mayor.

01:52.045 --> 01:53.412
You know that was
a fake phone call,
don't you?

01:53.414 --> 02:01.019
Yes, and I also know that the
new GNB headquarters project
was scrapped last month.

02:01.021 --> 02:02.621
Nice try.

02:16.603 --> 02:19.471
Check out Scarlett Johansson
at the Oscars.

02:19.473 --> 02:20.672
If I could
nail any celebrity,

02:20.674 --> 02:21.974
it would definitely
be Scarlett Johansson.

02:21.976 --> 02:26.178
Hot,
talented, and nobody does
that many Woody Allen movies

02:26.180 --> 02:28.147
without serious daddy issues.

02:28.149 --> 02:30.215
If I could nail any
celebrity, it would
be Lily.

02:30.217 --> 02:32.184
She's the
star of my heart.

02:32.186 --> 02:33.218
Aw!

02:33.220 --> 02:35.921
For me,
it'd be Hugh Jackman.

02:35.923 --> 02:37.656
You know,
I don't know, celebrities,

02:37.658 --> 02:40.592
they're into some
really weird sex
stuff.

02:40.594 --> 02:41.527
Trust me.

02:41.529 --> 02:43.862
How would you know that?

02:44.564 --> 02:46.598
This is embarrassing,
but I...

02:46.600 --> 02:48.500
I went home with
a celebrity one night.

02:48.502 --> 02:51.136
(GASPS) Oh, my God!
Seriously?

02:51.138 --> 02:54.606
Yeah. He wanted
to do this really
freaky thing with me,

02:54.608 --> 02:57.276
so I left. That's it.
End of story.

02:57.278 --> 02:59.111
No, no,
not end of story.

02:59.113 --> 03:03.048
I need to know
who, what, when and
in where. Spill it!

03:03.050 --> 03:04.550
Lily,
please settle down.

03:04.552 --> 03:06.451
You're
swallowing
too much air.

03:06.453 --> 03:07.886
But before you
go any further,

03:07.888 --> 03:10.589
I'm flattered,
but technically,
I'm not a celebrity.

03:10.591 --> 03:14.860
And plus, for the last time,
I put the mask on as a joke.

03:14.862 --> 03:17.129
Okay, not you, Barney.

03:17.131 --> 03:18.230
Okay, who is it?

03:18.232 --> 03:19.064
(HICCUPS)

03:19.066 --> 03:22.100
Okay,
now you gave
Lily the hiccups.

03:22.102 --> 03:24.570
Okay, I won't tell
you anything specific,

03:24.572 --> 03:27.706
but all I'll say is
he is Canadian-born,

03:27.708 --> 03:29.041
but you
definitely
know this guy,

03:29.043 --> 03:30.175
and he got me
back to his place

03:30.177 --> 03:33.879
by offering to show me
a very unique collection.

03:33.881 --> 03:34.813
What do you mean,
collection?

03:34.815 --> 03:36.548
Well, you know how
some people collect,

03:36.550 --> 03:38.584
like, stamps or coins?
It's like that.

03:38.586 --> 03:39.117
But I'm not telling.

03:39.119 --> 03:41.220
Well, at least tell
us the weird thing
he wanted to do.

03:41.222 --> 03:43.722
(SIGHS) I don't know
what you call it in
the States,

03:43.724 --> 03:45.691
but
we have a name
for it in Canada.

03:45.693 --> 03:47.693
Look,
I've already
said too much.

03:47.695 --> 03:51.730
So,
mystery celebrity who
collects a mystery item

03:51.732 --> 03:56.168
asked you
to do a mystery
Canadian sex act.

03:56.170 --> 03:57.202
Yes.
Tell us!

03:57.204 --> 03:58.136
(HICCUPS)

03:58.138 --> 03:59.538
Okay, I'll tell you.

03:59.540 --> 04:03.575
But only if you guess
all three parts correctly.

04:03.577 --> 04:05.310
Well,
that's just impossible.

04:05.312 --> 04:06.211
Exactly.

04:06.213 --> 04:08.447
I don't even know
any Canadian sex acts.

04:08.449 --> 04:10.249
Well,
you got your
Sloppy Dog Sled,

04:10.251 --> 04:13.151
your
Alberta Fur Trapper,
your Full Mountie...

04:13.153 --> 04:14.386
How do you know all these?

04:14.388 --> 04:17.789
Canadiansexacts.org,
it's bookmarked on
the top right.

04:17.791 --> 04:18.624
"Dot org"?

04:18.626 --> 04:19.625
Yeah. It's not for profit.

04:19.627 --> 04:22.194
They really
just want to get the
information out there.

04:22.196 --> 04:25.163
Hey, so,
I just had the
weirdest conversation.

04:25.165 --> 04:30.302
This woman at GNB told me that
the new bank building was
scrapped last month.

04:30.304 --> 04:32.170
That's crazy, right?

04:32.172 --> 04:33.872
Wait, what...
What was that look?

04:33.874 --> 04:35.073
Should we tell him?
I don't want to tell him.

04:35.075 --> 04:36.908
I think we should tell him.
We're not telling him.

04:36.910 --> 04:37.909
There was no look.

04:37.911 --> 04:39.678
Guys, what the hell?

04:39.680 --> 04:41.580
Okay,
it's time that
you know the truth.

04:41.582 --> 04:45.250
A few weeks ago,
Bilson called us
into his office.

04:45.252 --> 04:48.720
We're scrapping the plan
for the new GNB headquarters.

04:48.722 --> 04:50.856
This recession is
killing us.

04:50.858 --> 04:53.659
We're cutting
anything non-essential.

04:53.661 --> 04:55.661
And I have a lot of
tough choices to make

04:55.663 --> 04:58.897
at the bi-quarterly
retreat in Saint Croix.

04:58.899 --> 05:00.699
Man,
Ted is gonna
be devastated.

05:00.701 --> 05:03.268
Not when he hears it
coming from his best
friend.

05:03.270 --> 05:05.804
I have to tell him?
I have to tell him?

05:05.806 --> 05:07.306
You should tell him,
you're his best friend.

05:07.308 --> 05:08.774
Am not,
you're his best friend.

05:08.776 --> 05:09.841
Am not, you're his best...

05:09.843 --> 05:11.877
Am...
(SHUSHING)
Quiet, here he comes.

05:11.879 --> 05:13.779
What, the white dude
or the Asian fellow?

05:13.781 --> 05:15.881
See? I barely know the guy.

05:15.883 --> 05:18.283
Hey, Ted, what's up?
Hey, how're you doing?

05:18.285 --> 05:21.920
I'm frustrated.
Anything innovative
I put in my designs,

05:21.922 --> 05:24.222
Bilson just hacks
out with a machete.

05:24.224 --> 05:26.658
I hate
having to answer
to a guy like that.

05:26.660 --> 05:27.726
You should
drop the project.

05:27.728 --> 05:29.261
You should totally
drop the project.

05:29.263 --> 05:30.329
It's beneath you.

05:30.331 --> 05:31.897
Then it's settled.
To Ted Mosby's
new chapter.

05:31.899 --> 05:33.231
May the wind
be at your back,
and may the road...

05:33.233 --> 05:37.102
Are you kidding?
They just laid off
another architect at my firm.

05:37.104 --> 05:39.037
I mean,
Bilson's
a pain, sure,

05:39.039 --> 05:42.274
but without this project,
I'm probably out of a job.

05:42.276 --> 05:45.210
Right. Um, it's funny
that you mention the
project,

05:45.212 --> 05:46.945
because...
You're nailing it.

05:46.947 --> 05:48.013
Keep up the good work, buddy.

05:48.015 --> 05:50.649
Your hair and teeth
look fantastic today.

05:50.651 --> 05:53.552
You're shining
like a diamond!

05:54.420 --> 05:56.922
Thank you. I needed that.

05:56.924 --> 05:58.690
All right,
I'm going to head
upstairs and keep working.

05:58.692 --> 06:04.096
I've got to find a way to
introduce some wood into
Bilson's dark atrium.

06:04.098 --> 06:07.132
I think
you know what I meant.

06:07.134 --> 06:08.633
(EXHALES)

06:08.868 --> 06:10.268
What was that?

06:10.270 --> 06:11.103
I... I have a thought, okay?

06:11.105 --> 06:14.506
We're paying Ted's firm for
two more months of design
work, no matter what,

06:14.508 --> 06:19.077
so couldn't
we just let him keep
working and not tell him?

06:19.079 --> 06:19.878
He's had a rough year.

06:19.880 --> 06:22.447
Let's
let the guy be happy
a little while longer.

06:22.449 --> 06:24.216
Marshall, what
you're suggesting

06:24.218 --> 06:28.754
is an elaborate, long-term lie
that requires tremendous
commitment.

06:28.756 --> 06:31.356
A nice guy like you
can't pull that off.

06:31.358 --> 06:34.493
Sure I can.
Lie to me right now.

06:34.495 --> 06:36.795
Okay. I have a spaceship.

06:36.797 --> 06:38.296
What kind of fuel
powers your spaceship?

06:38.298 --> 06:39.898
Okay,
I don't have a spaceship.

06:39.900 --> 06:43.468
No! Stand your ground.
If someone questions you,

06:43.470 --> 06:46.204
distract them from the
original lie with more lies.

06:46.206 --> 06:49.174
Here, let me demonstrate.
I own a pony.

06:49.176 --> 06:50.475
Ask me a question.

06:50.477 --> 06:53.345
(SCOFFS) Okay. Um...

06:53.980 --> 06:54.880
What color is your pony?

06:54.882 --> 06:56.782
Well,
when I first
got Dandelion,

06:56.784 --> 06:58.150
she was a deep
chestnut brown,

06:58.152 --> 07:01.286
but sadly,
her stable is located
near a chemical plant

07:01.288 --> 07:03.155
which contaminated
the drinking water.

07:03.157 --> 07:04.790
So over time,
she's turned

07:04.792 --> 07:07.125
a sickly,
grayish-white color,

07:07.127 --> 07:08.326
(VOICE TREMBLING)
and there's nothing

07:08.328 --> 07:10.362
that the vet
can do to fix her.

07:10.364 --> 07:13.165
My God! I'm...
That's horrible.

07:13.167 --> 07:15.934
Is Dandelion
going to be okay?

07:15.936 --> 07:18.203
Okay.
All right.
You are good!

07:18.205 --> 07:18.804
Huh?

07:18.806 --> 07:22.974
Dandelion's not
even sick, is she?

07:22.976 --> 07:27.345
So the
building's really dead
and you guys lied to me?

07:27.347 --> 07:29.381
We just did it to
protect you, Ted.

07:29.383 --> 07:33.118
I can't believe this.
I just got screwed by
my two best friends,

07:33.120 --> 07:35.654
and I didn't even know it.

07:36.122 --> 07:39.791
In Canada,
that's called a
"Sneaky Snowplow."

07:44.397 --> 07:49.067
That building
was my dream job,
and now, it's just gone.

07:49.069 --> 07:50.168
We're so sorry, Ted.

07:50.170 --> 07:52.471
(SIGHS) I need a drink.

07:52.905 --> 07:53.839
Poor Ted.

07:53.841 --> 07:57.142
Would I seem
heartless if I switched us
back to Canadian Sex Acts?

07:57.144 --> 07:59.377
Not at all.
I'm surprised
you waited this long.

07:59.379 --> 08:01.112
What the hell is
a Two-Hand Zamboni?

08:01.114 --> 08:07.285
Let's just say the only thing
the woman is wearing is
skates on her hands.

08:07.287 --> 08:09.020
A Manitoba Milk Bag?

08:09.022 --> 08:10.555
Okay, it's like
a Chicago Mustache,

08:10.557 --> 08:14.292
but the
person on the bottom
is wearing a snowsuit.

08:14.294 --> 08:16.761
A Newfoundland Lobster Trap?

08:16.763 --> 08:18.163
Don't know.
Don't want to know.

08:18.165 --> 08:20.265
Those Newfies
are out of control.

08:20.267 --> 08:22.367
Okay!
Okay, I'm going to
make my first guess.

08:22.369 --> 08:23.468
Okay,
but I'll only tell you

08:23.470 --> 08:28.173
if you
correctly guess the person,
the act and the collection.

08:28.175 --> 08:30.308
Okay,
I'm going to
go. Bryan Adams.

08:30.310 --> 08:38.116
He collects baseball cards,
and he wanted to do
a Greasy Kayak.

08:38.118 --> 08:38.750
No.

08:38.752 --> 08:44.523
Wayne Gretzky,
vintage Hot Wheels,
a Squatting Eskimo.

08:44.525 --> 08:45.357
No.

08:45.359 --> 08:46.291
Mmm! Kiefer Sutherland,

08:46.293 --> 08:51.263
souvenir shot glasses,
and a Sticky Flapjack.

08:51.265 --> 08:54.199
No.
That I would have done.

08:55.101 --> 08:56.067
Wait.

08:56.069 --> 08:58.169
Wait,
if they pulled the plug
on the project a month ago,

08:58.171 --> 08:59.571
why have I been
going in once a week

08:59.573 --> 09:02.007
to meet with the New
Headquarters Task Force?

09:02.009 --> 09:05.143
Well, obviously
you couldn't come
in and pitch to Bilson.

09:05.145 --> 09:08.313
So,
we invented
the task force.

09:08.315 --> 09:12.384
Then it was just a question
of putting together the team.

09:12.386 --> 09:13.718
<i>MARSHALL:</i>
<i>You know Roy Waterman,</i>

09:13.720 --> 09:16.254
<i>Vice-President of</i>
<i>Capital and Risk?</i>

09:16.256 --> 09:19.257
<i>He's actually</i>
<i>Roy the janitor.</i>

09:19.259 --> 09:20.392
Hey. Excuse me, Roy.

09:20.394 --> 09:23.194
How'd you like to
make a few extra bucks?

09:23.196 --> 09:24.162
(SIGHS)

09:24.164 --> 09:26.698
How naked do
I have to get?

09:26.700 --> 09:30.468
<i>Louisa Mendoza, Executive</i>
<i>Vice-President of Assets?</i>

09:30.470 --> 09:33.505
<i>She's actually</i>
<i>Louisa the lunch lady.</i>

09:33.507 --> 09:38.577
Louisa, I need
your help with something,
but you can't tell anybody.

09:38.579 --> 09:40.512
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

09:40.514 --> 09:43.248
Exactly.
This is a big secret.

09:43.250 --> 09:46.117
How do you say
"secret" in Spanish?

09:46.119 --> 09:47.552
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

09:47.554 --> 09:50.455
Ah. Yes,<i> albóndigas.</i>

09:50.457 --> 09:55.026
This will be our
little<i> albondigas.</i>

09:55.227 --> 09:57.629
Hey,
can I have a couple
of meatballs, please?

09:57.631 --> 10:02.467
<i>And Arthur Naismith,</i>
<i>the eccentric genius guru</i>
<i>of corporate investments?</i>

10:02.469 --> 10:08.139
<i>He's actually Crazy Arty,</i>
<i>15th Street's own one-man</i>
<i>band.</i>

10:08.141 --> 10:09.574
Excuse me.
(SHRIEKS) Ah!

10:09.576 --> 10:10.575
Do you have
a minute to talk?

10:10.577 --> 10:15.180
Actually,
my assistant, Reginald,
makes all my appointments.

10:18.818 --> 10:20.418
<i>We rounded out the</i>
<i>group with a few</i>
<i>interns</i>

10:20.420 --> 10:25.457
<i>and paid everyone 50 bucks to</i>
<i>act super-interested in what</i>
<i>you were saying.</i>

10:31.631 --> 10:35.567
Reginald, get me out
of this for next week.

10:35.569 --> 10:36.568
That was some of
the most inspired

10:36.570 --> 10:41.940
design work I've done
in my entire career.
I was so excited.

10:43.743 --> 10:47.512
Alex Trebek, a Musty
Goaltender, Beanie
Babies!

10:47.514 --> 10:48.480
Nope.
Damn it!

10:48.482 --> 10:53.385
Wait. So
that explains the thing
that happened with Louisa.

10:53.387 --> 10:56.121
Good job, buddy.
Nice, nice!

10:58.357 --> 11:03.995
Listen, Louisa.
What are we going
to do about this?

11:05.364 --> 11:07.732
Don't act
like you don't know
what I'm talking about.

11:07.734 --> 11:10.502
I know you feel it, too.

11:10.504 --> 11:12.370
(SIGHS) What the hell?

11:12.372 --> 11:13.805
(LOUISA GASPS)

11:13.807 --> 11:15.273
(SPEAKING SPANISH)
No, I can't...

11:15.275 --> 11:18.610
I'm already engaged
to Mr. Barney.

11:18.612 --> 11:19.844
Ah, who cares...

11:19.846 --> 11:21.079
we live but once!

11:21.081 --> 11:23.114
(BOTH MOANING)

11:23.516 --> 11:26.718
No! No!
No, this is wrong!

11:26.720 --> 11:30.388
For God's sake,
you're on the task force!

11:32.124 --> 11:34.392
Is there anything
else you want to
tell me?

11:34.394 --> 11:40.265
Well, you know
how you played third base
for the GNB softball team?

11:40.267 --> 11:40.732
Yeah.

11:40.734 --> 11:42.534
There is no
GNB softball team.

11:42.536 --> 11:45.737
We just rented out a field,
rounded up a bunch of guys

11:45.739 --> 11:48.440
and told them to
make you the hero.

11:48.442 --> 11:50.709
So my
game-winning
walk was a lie?

11:50.711 --> 11:53.344
We're sorry,
Ted, but we knew that
you'd be out of work soon,

11:53.346 --> 11:55.313
and we just...
We just wanted to
make you feel good.

11:55.315 --> 11:57.015
You know,
that's what friends do.

11:57.017 --> 11:57.682
Lie to each other?

11:57.684 --> 12:00.351
Sometimes,
yeah, to protect
each other's feelings.

12:00.353 --> 12:02.587
No way! You never
lie to your friends.

12:02.589 --> 12:03.688
I would never not
be honest with you.

12:03.690 --> 12:08.326
Really? What about
that open mic night
at the comedy club?

12:08.328 --> 12:09.794
<i>Are you like me, folks?</i>

12:09.796 --> 12:11.362
<i>Have you ever</i>
<i>thought about</i>
<i>how many</i>

12:11.364 --> 12:17.402
<i>different</i>
<i>kinds of fish there are,</i>
<i>and the names of those fish?</i>

12:17.404 --> 12:19.204
<i>(STIFLING LAUGHTER)</i>

12:19.206 --> 12:21.306
<i>Let's, uh, let's</i>
<i>take a little ride.</i>

12:23.576 --> 12:25.677
<i>"Trout." Am I right?</i>

12:25.679 --> 12:29.447
<i>"Sturgeon."</i>
<i>I don't think so, pal.</i>

12:29.449 --> 12:30.181
<i>"Salmon."</i>

12:30.183 --> 12:32.751
<i>Ah!</i>
<i>I'm going to</i>
<i>say that again.</i>

12:33.519 --> 12:34.252
<i>"Salmon."</i>

12:34.254 --> 12:35.920
<i>Who thought that was</i>
<i>a good idea, right?</i>

12:35.922 --> 12:41.025
<i>"Bass." This guy over here</i>
<i>knows what I'm talking about.</i>

12:41.027 --> 12:44.729
<i>"Halibut."</i>
<i>Thank you,</i>
<i>good night.</i>

12:48.234 --> 12:48.900
How was I?

12:48.902 --> 12:50.969
Oh! You were great.
Really funny.

12:50.971 --> 12:52.504
You killed

12:52.506 --> 12:54.939
everyone's
Thursday night.

12:55.808 --> 12:58.676
Time out.
You didn't like the fish list?

12:58.678 --> 13:03.615
It was horrible! You
just read a list of
fish.

13:03.617 --> 13:05.183
(WHOOSHING)

13:05.951 --> 13:09.320
Anyway,
you guys just
proved my point, okay?

13:09.322 --> 13:11.723
You lied to me to
protect my feelings.

13:11.725 --> 13:12.657
This is completely different!

13:12.659 --> 13:15.794
I just wasted
a month of my life
working on a dead project.

13:15.796 --> 13:19.330
That's time I could've spent
trying to bring my firm new
business.

13:19.332 --> 13:22.167
Instead,
I'm going to go in
there tomorrow morning,

13:22.169 --> 13:23.234
I'm probably
going to get fired.

13:23.236 --> 13:28.740
Best-case scenario, my boss is
going to ream me out in front
of everybody.

13:29.408 --> 13:32.343
Back home,
we call that a...
"Saskatoon Totem Pole."

13:32.345 --> 13:34.179
ROBIN: Yes.
It's on here.

13:39.718 --> 13:41.653
Good morning,
lying bastards.

13:41.655 --> 13:46.191
Anything you want to lie
about before I head off
to work to get fired?

13:46.193 --> 13:47.225
That's a nice shirt.
You're the devil.

13:47.227 --> 13:50.495
Ted, what if we told you
that we found you a new
project at GNB

13:50.497 --> 13:53.765
where you
would be redesigning
part of the 20th floor?

13:53.767 --> 13:57.335
Well, if that's a lie,
it's an incredibly
dull one.

13:57.337 --> 13:58.770
What exactly
would I be doing?

13:58.772 --> 14:01.739
This is the 18th floor
ETR.

14:01.741 --> 14:04.175
Basically,
Bilson wants a
room just like this,

14:04.177 --> 14:06.311
only two stories up,
on our floor.

14:06.313 --> 14:07.345
Wait, what's an ETR?

14:07.347 --> 14:09.480
It's
the Employee
Transition Room.

14:09.482 --> 14:10.281
What does that mean?

14:10.283 --> 14:13.284
Well, it's a space where
a supervisor and an employee

14:13.286 --> 14:19.858
engage in a knowledge transfer
about an impending vocational
paradigm shift.

14:19.860 --> 14:21.659
People get
fired in here.

14:21.661 --> 14:22.293
That's horrible.

14:22.295 --> 14:25.463
Why do you need a room
specifically for firing
people?

14:25.465 --> 14:28.566
Well,
GNB feels that
people need a safe,

14:28.568 --> 14:31.369
secure space to
deal with the news.

14:31.371 --> 14:34.739
Yeah. It gets
pretty real in here.

14:34.741 --> 14:37.242
<i>(UPBEAT SPANISH MUSIC PLAYING)</i>

15:20.219 --> 15:22.086
<i>OLDER TED: So,</i>
<i>I reluctantly</i>
<i>agreed to</i>

15:22.088 --> 15:24.122
<i>design a room where</i>
<i>people would be fired.</i>

15:24.124 --> 15:26.357
<i>But I was</i>
<i>determined to</i>
<i>make it my own.</i>

15:26.359 --> 15:28.826
Now, when you leave
the dismissal space,

15:28.828 --> 15:30.828
you'll exit into
what I'm calling

15:30.830 --> 15:34.732
the Rebirth
Tranquility
Hallway.

15:34.734 --> 15:35.800
Uh-oh.

15:35.802 --> 15:38.603
Here, you'll find
a soothing oval
chamber

15:38.605 --> 15:40.505
with a trained
grief counselor.

15:40.507 --> 15:43.641
It's right here, past
the New Beginnings
Fountain.

15:43.643 --> 15:44.342
Uh-oh.

15:44.344 --> 15:48.780
And there you have it.
Instead of a drab,
dark prison cell,

15:48.782 --> 15:55.954
a nurturing
womb birthing
you into a new life.

15:55.956 --> 15:56.955
I love it.

15:56.957 --> 15:58.589
Really?
Yeah.

15:58.591 --> 16:00.591
Nice work, Ted.
Thank you.

16:00.593 --> 16:01.659
Can you add some
of these touches

16:01.661 --> 16:04.329
to the existing
18th Floor ETR
as well?

16:04.331 --> 16:06.331
Absolutely.
Great.

16:06.333 --> 16:08.533
Let's take a look.

16:11.737 --> 16:14.238
Okay, so I'm
thinking this wall...

16:14.240 --> 16:15.006
You're fired!

16:15.008 --> 16:17.442
What?
I wanted this room!

16:17.444 --> 16:20.244
This exact room,
two floors up!

16:20.246 --> 16:22.413
But...
You're fired!

16:22.415 --> 16:24.749
Now, get the hell
out of here.

16:24.751 --> 16:26.718
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

16:28.287 --> 16:29.354
Hey, honey.

16:31.590 --> 16:33.424
<i>(CRASHING)</i>

16:34.660 --> 16:36.394
Anyone from the band Rush,

16:36.396 --> 16:40.932
a Montreal Meatpie,
and superhero lunch boxes.

16:40.934 --> 16:41.699
No.

16:41.701 --> 16:46.537
Okay. Rick Moranis,
the Reverse Rick Moranis,

16:46.539 --> 16:48.039
antique Judaica.

16:48.041 --> 16:49.607
No.
I give up.

16:49.609 --> 16:52.944
I've been guessing for
three days. I'm done.

16:52.946 --> 16:56.414
If that means I never
get to know, so be it.

16:56.416 --> 16:56.981
Fine.

16:56.983 --> 16:59.884
(HICCUPPING)
Tell us! Tell us! Tell us!

16:59.886 --> 17:01.552
Okay,
you really
want to know?

17:01.554 --> 17:02.887
ALL: Yes!

17:02.889 --> 17:03.921
Okay.

17:03.923 --> 17:07.492
But this information
does not leave this
table.

17:07.494 --> 17:08.860
(HICCUPS)

17:08.862 --> 17:11.863
Oh, my God.
I am so excited.

17:13.465 --> 17:14.399
I'm going to read it.
Read it.

17:14.401 --> 17:15.333
I'm going to read it.
Read it.

17:15.335 --> 17:17.668
I'm going to read it.
Here we go.

17:17.670 --> 17:23.741
"The Frozen Snowshoe,
Old King Clancy,
Harvey's trays."

17:26.912 --> 17:28.479
Right.

17:28.481 --> 17:31.616
I don't know what
any of those words mean.

17:31.618 --> 17:33.851
Is one of those
supposed to be
a celebrity?

17:33.853 --> 17:38.089
Yeah, who the hell
is Old King Clancy?

17:38.091 --> 17:40.925
No, that's
not the person,
that's the sex act.

17:40.927 --> 17:45.730
It's the same as
a Sacramento Turtleneck,
except with maple syrup.

17:45.732 --> 17:48.966
So the celebrity
was Harvey Strays?

17:48.968 --> 17:51.402
No,
that's what
he collected.

17:51.404 --> 17:52.170
Harvey's trays.

17:52.172 --> 17:56.874
You know, those classic orange
trays you get whenever you
eat at Harvey's?

17:56.876 --> 17:58.242
The restaurant?

17:58.244 --> 18:01.079
Oh, come on,
you're road-tripping down
the Trans-Canada Highway,

18:01.081 --> 18:03.648
you get a hunger on
between Milverton
and Wawa,

18:03.650 --> 18:07.351
where are you gonna
strap on a feed bag,
huh? Harvey's.

18:07.353 --> 18:09.353
"Over 12,000 Served!"

18:09.855 --> 18:11.823
So the celebrity was...

18:11.825 --> 18:14.158
The Frozen Snowshoe.

18:14.160 --> 18:17.662
Oh, my God!
You guys have never
heard of The Frozen Snowshoe?

18:17.664 --> 18:21.532
He's only the most
famous professional
wrestler in Canada.

18:21.534 --> 18:24.836
I met him
after he defeated
Reckless Rick Rogers

18:24.838 --> 18:29.841
in the
Kamloops Memorial Arena
back in '02. Classic match.

18:29.843 --> 18:33.144
So you're saying
The Frozen Snowshoe

18:33.146 --> 18:37.748
invited you
back to his place to
look at Harvey's trays,

18:37.750 --> 18:40.485
and asked you to do
an Old King Clancy?

18:40.487 --> 18:45.389
Exactly.
And I'm serious,
you cannot tell anyone.

18:46.091 --> 18:48.159
Well,
my hiccups are gone.

18:48.161 --> 18:50.261
Possibly forever.

18:50.263 --> 18:52.697
Canada!
You did it again.

18:52.699 --> 18:55.566
You even found
a way to ruin this.

18:55.568 --> 18:59.871
Why?
Why do we let
you be a country?

18:59.873 --> 19:01.639
Hey, Mr. Mister.
Hey.

19:01.641 --> 19:02.840
Shouldn't you be upstairs,

19:02.842 --> 19:05.076
designing your
big, fancy ETR?

19:05.078 --> 19:06.544
I'm off the project.

19:06.546 --> 19:07.512
What?

19:07.514 --> 19:08.679
Bilson fired me.

19:08.681 --> 19:09.514
You're kidding me.

19:09.516 --> 19:13.751
So what does this mean for
you at your firm? Are you
going to get laid off?

19:13.753 --> 19:16.521
Actually, I just quit.

19:16.523 --> 19:16.854
Why?

19:16.856 --> 19:20.925
Because I can't
work for big, heartless
corporate clients anymore.

19:20.927 --> 19:22.426
When I was pitching
to your "task force,"

19:22.428 --> 19:25.163
I was doing
the most inspired
work of my career.

19:25.165 --> 19:29.167
In a way,
you idiots reminded me
how much fun my job can be

19:29.169 --> 19:33.137
when I'm not answering
to the Bilsons of the
world, so

19:33.139 --> 19:34.572
I quit.

19:34.574 --> 19:36.007
Wow.

19:36.009 --> 19:37.575
They fired you,
didn't they?

19:37.577 --> 19:38.342
Yes, sir.

19:38.344 --> 19:42.413
But I got
a sweet severance package
and I've made a big decision.

19:42.415 --> 19:44.115
I'm going to
start my own firm.

19:44.117 --> 19:45.683
Whoa, buddy!
That's exciting.

19:45.685 --> 19:47.785
In this economy?

19:47.787 --> 19:50.021
So you're not mad?

19:50.023 --> 19:53.491
As it turns out,
I'm grateful.

19:55.027 --> 19:57.261
So how'd it all go down
between you and Bilson?

19:57.263 --> 20:00.264
Well, after he proposed
a vocational paradigm shift,

20:00.266 --> 20:03.834
I made
an impromptu presentation
using a four-pronged approach

20:03.836 --> 20:05.770
that really
brought him
to his knees.

20:05.772 --> 20:07.071
Hit him with a chair?
Yep.

20:07.073 --> 20:09.140
That's my boy.

20:13.745 --> 20:16.714
And this one,
I got on the drive
from Milverton to Wawa.

20:16.716 --> 20:21.852
Wow. That's
pretty impressive,
The Frozen Snowshoe.

20:21.854 --> 20:25.256
Please,
we're friends.
Just call me "Shoe."

20:25.258 --> 20:26.724
Have a seat.

20:31.830 --> 20:33.998
So, Shoe,

20:34.000 --> 20:36.667
how would you
like to give me

20:38.537 --> 20:40.771
an Old King Clancy?

20:44.042 --> 20:46.210
I think you should go.
